The UV–vis spectrum of carbon dots (Fig. 7
                        a) showed a strong optical absorption with two distinct shoulders in the UV region at 250 nm and 300 nm, with a tail extending into the visible region. The peak at 250 nm was attributed to π-π* transition of the sp2 carbons in the carbon dots [6], responsible for the trapping of excited-state energy by surface states [42]. These results confirmed that the carbon dots contained the unsaturated carbons, similarly identified in the FT-IR spectra and XPS survey. The absorption spectrum showed another peak at 350 nm, corresponding to the n-π* transition. The inset images in Fig. 7a show the blue-green emission of the carbon dots under UV irradiation (left) and under visible light (right). Using quinine sulfate as a reference, the quantum yield of the carbon dots was 33%, which is excellent compared to the carbon dots prepared from other polymers in previous studies (Table 4
                        ). The relatively high quantum yields of our carbon dots were due to the high doping of nitrogen and sulfur in the carbon dots, leading to the formation of favorable emissive states [43,44].

In this study, the selectivity and sensitivity of carbon dots toward Ag+ was investigated. Firstly, fluorescence responses of the carbon dots upon addition of different metal ions were studied and results were presented in Fig. 10
                        a and b. Only Ag+ induced a strong photoluminescence quenching of the carbon dots compared with the other metal cations at the same concentration of 20 μM, signifying an outstanding selectivity of the carbon dots to Ag+ ions. The fluorescence intensity of carbon dots at around 491 nm emission wavelength decreased gradually with an increase in Ag+ concentration, which means that addition of Ag+ could effectively quench the fluorescence of carbon dots. Fig. 10c and d manifest gradual decrease in the fluorescence intensity of the carbon dots as concentrations of Ag+ were varied from 0 to 6 μM. Based on the Stern-Volmer equation: I0/I = 1+Ksv[Ag+], a slope, which is equivalent to a Stern-Volmer constant (Ksv), is equal to 12.8 × 104 M−1. A large Stern-Volmer constant suggests the fluorescence quenching of carbon dots by Ag+ is due to the static quenching process [50]. The calculated LOD for silver ions (Ag+) is 2.8 μM, which is comparable to recently reported LODs for fluorescence-based Ag+ sensing using other carbon dots (Table 5
                        ). Our carbon dots were label-free and showed much better selectivity toward Ag+, compared to the reports by Arumugam N. et al. [51] Cayuela A. et al. [12], and Borse V. et al. [52] There have been two proposed sensing mechanisms of carbon dots toward Ag+: 1) the thiol/-Ag+ interaction [53] and 2) reduction of Ag+ to Ag° [54]. In our case, since there was no change in the solution color and in the UV–vis absorbance upon the addition of Ag+ to carbon dots, this ensures that the sensing mechanism was via the thiol-Ag+ interaction. This is consistent with the fact that our carbon dots are highly sulfur-doped as confirmed by FTIR and XPS characterizations because of the use of sulfuric acid as a catalyst during the synthesis. The Ag+ selectivity of carbon dots is due to the flexible coordination sphere of Ag+ compared with other metal ions [12] and the soft acidity of Ag+ and soft basicity of thiol groups [53]. Furthermore, the presence of carboxylic acids on the surface further enhanced the interaction between the carbon dots and Ag+ [53]. These favorable interactions endow highly selective and sensitive detection of the carbon dots toward Ag+.
